{"timestamp": "2025-12-01 13:25:30.992248", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Submission accepted.\n\nSummary of what I submitted\n- is_anomaly: true\n- faulty_devices: [\"switch_1\", \"switch_2\"]\n- root_cause_name: [\"p4_table_entry_misconfig\", \"p4_header_definition_error\"]\n\nRecommended next steps (concise)\n1. Capture an egress frame on the switch->host link (tcpdump on the switch or host) and verify ethernet.dstAddr bytes — confirm they match the IPv4-derived values (0a:00:00:01 etc.) rather than the host MAC (00:00:0a:00:00:01).\n2. Inspect the P4 action signature and table entry population:\n   - Ensure the action parameter dstAddr is defined as a 48-bit mac_t (or bit<48>) and not as a 32-bit field or ipv4_t.\n   - If action takes a bit<48> but receives a bit<32> value from table install, correct the runtime table entries to supply full 48-bit MACs.\n3. Check bloom_filter.json (runtime config) — restore or correct it if it should supply MAC mappings.\n4. Reinstall corrected table entries with proper MAC addresses (00:00:0a:00:00:01 and 00:00:0a:00:00:02) and re-test ping.\n5. (Optional) Add defensive code in P4 to avoid assigning mismatched-width values, and improve logging to print MACs in 6-byte format.\n\nIf you want, I can guide you through the exact commands to capture frames and inspect/fix P4 action/table definitions and to craft the correct table entries.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 2800, "output_tokens": 344, "total_tokens": 3144, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 2688}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 0}}}
